<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="key">
<key pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyStep pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
1. Coxal plate 1 strongly reduced, hidden behind plate 2; coxal plate 4 distally expanded without posterior concavity, larger than 2 and 3; coxal plates 5–7 much longer than deep, not lobate; dactylus and unguis lacking on mandible palp, gnathopod 1 and gnathopod 2; unguis lacking on pereopods 3–7; pereopod 5 basis dominating 6 and 7........... 
<taxonomicName authority="Stebbing, 1888" authorityName="Stebbing" authorityYear="1888" box="[1183,1426,783,805]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Cardenio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1183,1273,783,804]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Cardenio</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stebbing, T. R. R." box="[1279,1426,783,805]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 1737" refId="ref50287" refString="Stebbing, T. R. R. (1888) Report on the Amphipoda collected by H. M. S. Challenger during the years 1873 - 76. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of the H. M. S. Challenger During the Years 1873 - 1876, Zoology, 29, 1 - 1737." type="journal article" year="1888">Stebbing, 1888</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
*
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead pageId="5" pageNumber="6">- Coxal plate 1 subequal to 2 and 3; coxal plate 4 shorter than 3, with more or less strong posterior concavity; coxal plates 5 and 6 posterolobate, often strongly; dactylus and unguis present on mandible palp and all gnathopods and pereopods; pereopod 7 basis dominating 5 and 6 to some degree (often a large degree)................................................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
2. Pereopods 3–7 short, dactylus/unguis stubby (
<figureCitation box="[668,736,900,922]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), or pre-stubby (
<figureCitation box="[897,966,900,922]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
) short, with curved counter-seta on dactylus........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Just, 2022" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[1068,1160,929,951]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" status="new subfamily" subFamily="Tironinae">Tironinae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1166,1315,929,951]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1166,1315,929,951]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="subFamily">new subfamily</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(key below)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" box="[151,1436,959,981]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,959,981]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">- Pereopods 3–7 elongate with simple, elongate dactylus/unguis................................................. 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" box="[151,1436,988,1010]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,988,1010]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">3. Gnathopods simple without definite corner or defining robust seta............................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,724,2041]" box="[151,1436,1017,1039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1017,1039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">- One or both gnathopods subchelate, with definite corner or defining robust seta.................................... 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
